Note:
F# Semantic Analyzer - semantic analysis over the F# translation AST

Operates directly on the AST shapes the post-#442 parser produces: every
node is the 48-byte record [type @0, value @8, children @16, child_count
@24, parent @32, metadata @40], literal and identifier nodes carry the
40-byte lexer token record in the value slot, children live in canonical
Lists, function bindings arrive desugared to name + AST_LAMBDA, pipe
nodes carry the pipe operator's token TYPE TAG (a small integer, not a
token pointer) in the value slot, and infix operators arrive as
AST_APPLICATION nodes whose first child is an operator identifier.

Analysis provided:
- Unification-based type inference with type variables over the full
  expression grammar (literals, identifiers, operators as functions,
  curried application, lambdas, let/and chains with rec pre-binding,
  match, if/elif, tuples, lists, arrays, records, pipes, sequences,
  try/with/finally, while, for, interpolated strings, quotations)
- Pattern validation and variable binding for every pattern shape the
  parser emits, including or-patterns and :? type-test patterns
- Discriminated-union constructor registration and per-use checking
- Match exhaustiveness analysis (irrefutable cover, bool literal cover,
  option cover, declared-union case cover) and redundant-arm detection
- Duplicate record field detection, guard bool-typing, condition
  bool-typing, branch type joins
- Unused-local-binding detection (underscore-prefixed names exempt)
- Units-of-measure and computation/async expression analysis for the
  declared AST_MEASURE and AST_COMPUTATION_EXPRESSION shapes

Type values are polymorphic the same way hir_nodes type positions are:
values below 65536 are the bare primitive type codes declared below;
larger values are pointers to composite type records whose first field
is the type tag. Every record this analyzer allocates is registered in
one ownership pool so destruction and re-analysis are leak-free.

Dependencies:
- fsharp_parser.runa (AST constants and node layout contract)
- fsharp_lexer.runa (token record accessors and token type constants)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/hashtable.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/internal/string_utils.runa (string_concat for diagnostics)
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/fsharp/fsharp_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/fsharp/fsharp_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/hashtable.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: F# Type System Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Primitive types (bare codes, always below 65536)
Constant TYPE_INT as Integer is 7001
Constant TYPE_FLOAT as Integer is 7002
Constant TYPE_STRING as Integer is 7003
Constant TYPE_BOOL as Integer is 7004
Constant TYPE_CHAR as Integer is 7005
Constant TYPE_UNIT as Integer is 7006
Constant TYPE_BYTE as Integer is 7007
Constant TYPE_DECIMAL as Integer is 7008

Note: Compound types (tags of heap records)
Constant TYPE_LIST as Integer is 7101
Constant TYPE_ARRAY as Integer is 7102
Constant TYPE_OPTION as Integer is 7103
Constant TYPE_TUPLE as Integer is 7104
Constant TYPE_FUNCTION as Integer is 7105
Constant TYPE_RECORD as Integer is 7106
Constant TYPE_UNION as Integer is 7107
Constant TYPE_SEQUENCE as Integer is 7108
Constant TYPE_ARRAY2D as Integer is 7109
Constant TYPE_ARRAY3D as Integer is 7110
Constant TYPE_MAP as Integer is 7111
Constant TYPE_SET as Integer is 7112

Note: Special types
Constant TYPE_GENERIC as Integer is 7201
Constant TYPE_MEASURE as Integer is 7202
Constant TYPE_CONSTRAINT as Integer is 7203
Constant TYPE_COMPUTATION as Integer is 7204
Constant TYPE_ASYNC as Integer is 7205
Constant TYPE_TASK as Integer is 7206
Constant TYPE_OBSERVABLE as Integer is 7207

Note: Error and unknown types
Constant TYPE_ERROR as Integer is 7901
Constant TYPE_UNKNOWN as Integer is 7902
Constant TYPE_ANY as Integer is 7903

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic Analyzer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Holds every cross-cutting analysis structure: symbol_table (module-level
scope), scope_stack (nested local scopes for save/restore), type_env
(named-type and constructor bindings), constraint_solver (substitution
store, allocation pool, match registry, definition registry),
module_table (module/namespace/open cross-reference), per-pass error and
warning lists, and the measure_system (units-of-measure registry). All
fields are pointers; the record is 64 bytes total.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Offsets: symbol_table (0), scope_stack (8), type_env (16),
constraint_solver (24), module_table (32), error_list (40),
warning_list (48), measure_system (56).

The constraint solver is a 48-byte record: substitution List indexed by
type-variable id (0), next fresh variable id (8), match registry List of
16-byte [match node, scrutinee type] pairs (16), definitions List of
40-byte symbol records (24), the allocation pool List that owns every
ad-hoc record this analyzer creates (32), and the env-types List (40) of
pooled 16-byte [scope depth, bound type] pairs - one per live binding,
truncated on pop_scope - which generalization scans to determine which
type variables are bound by the environment.

Symbol records are 40 bytes: bound type (0), is_used flag (8), name
string (16), is_local flag (24), and the type-scheme quantifier record
(32): 0 for monomorphic bindings, otherwise a pooled [count, id...]
record of the let-generalized type-variable ids that instantiation
refreshes at every use. Composite type records start with the type tag
at offset 0 followed by tag-specific payload fields.
@End Implementation

Type called "FSharpSemanticAnalyzer":
    symbol_table as Integer         Note: Module-level symbol table
    scope_stack as Integer          Note: Stack of nested local scopes
    type_env as Integer             Note: Type and constructor environment
    constraint_solver as Integer    Note: Substitutions, pools, registries
    module_table as Integer         Note: Module and namespace table
    error_list as Integer           Note: Semantic errors
    warning_list as Integer         Note: Semantic warnings
    measure_system as Integer       Note: Units of measure registry
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Analyzer Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the analyzer record then wires up all sub-structures in order:
three hashtables (symbol_table, type_env, module_table), the scope
stack, the constraint solver, two diagnostic lists, and the measure
registry. Finally seeds the type environment with the built-in F# type
names and constructors so user code resolves them without declarations.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_fsharp_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create new F# semantic analyzer

    Let analyzer_size be 64  Note: 8 fields x 8 bytes each
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let symbol_table be proc hashtable_create from Dict
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, symbol_table

    Let scope_stack be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, scope_stack

    Let type_env be proc hashtable_create from Dict
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, type_env

    Let constraint_solver be proc create_constraint_solver with analyzer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, constraint_solver

    Let module_table be proc hashtable_create from Dict
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, module_table

    Let error_list be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, error_list

    Let warning_list be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, warning_list

    Let measure_system be proc create_measure_system with analyzer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, measure_system

    proc setup_fsharp_builtins with analyzer

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The constraint solver bundles every piece of analysis state that must
survive across passes: the type-variable substitution store (a List
indexed by variable id so integer ids need no string hashing), the next
fresh-variable counter, the match-expression registry the late
exhaustiveness pass walks, the definitions registry the unused-binding
pass walks, and the allocation pool that owns every record the analyzer
heap-allocates (type records, symbol records, constructor descriptors,
registry pairs, diagnostic strings built with string_concat). Pooled
ownership makes destroy and clear leak-free without per-record
ownership bookkeeping.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_constraint_solver" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create the unification and registry store (48-byte record)

    Let solver be proc allocate from Layout with 48
    If solver is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let subst be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with solver, 0, subst
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with solver, 8, 0   Note: next variable id

    Let match_registry be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with solver, 16, match_registry

    Let definitions be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with solver, 24, definitions

    Let alloc_pool be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with solver, 32, alloc_pool

    Let env_types be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with solver, 40, env_types

    Return solver
End Process

@Reasoning:
The measure registry maps base measure names to their descriptor (the
name string itself serves as the descriptor for base units). Measures
are user-declared in F# via [<Measure>] attributes, so the registry
starts empty and lookup failures over the AST_MEASURE shape surface as
"Unknown unit of measure" diagnostics - exactly F#'s behaviour for
undeclared units.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_measure_system" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create units of measure registry
    Return proc hashtable_create from Dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers every memory block the analyzer allocates into the solver's
ownership pool so destroy_fsharp_semantic_analyzer and
clear_analysis_results can release everything in one sweep without
per-record lifetime tracking. Returns the block unchanged so call sites
compose as expressions.
@End Reasoning

Process called "pool_allocate" takes analyzer as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate a pooled record owned by the analyzer

    Let block be proc allocate from Layout with size
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let solver be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let alloc_pool be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with solver, 32
    proc list_append from List with alloc_pool, block

    Return block
End Process

@Reasoning:
Diagnostic messages composed at runtime (name-bearing errors and
warnings) are built with string_concat, which returns a Layout-owned
allocation; registering the result in the pool keeps diagnostics alive
exactly as long as the analyzer and frees them with it.
@End Reasoning

Process called "pool_concat" takes analyzer as Integer, left as Integer, right as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Concatenate two strings into a pooled diagnostic string

    Let joined be proc string_concat from StringUtils with left, right
    If joined is equal to 0:
        Return left
    End If

    Let solver be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let alloc_pool be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with solver, 32
    proc list_append from List with alloc_pool, joined

    Return joined
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reverse of create_*: releases every pooled record, the solver's four
Lists and the solver itself, every remaining scope hashtable on the
stack, the four hashtables, and the diagnostic lists, then the analyzer
record. Each field is null-checked so partially-constructed analyzers
(allocation failure midway through create_*) destroy cleanly.
@End Reasoning

Process called "destroy_fsharp_semantic_analyzer" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy analyzer and free all owned memory

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let solver be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    If solver is not equal to 0:
        Let alloc_pool be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with solver, 32
        If alloc_pool is not equal to 0:
            Let pool_count be proc list_length from List with alloc_pool
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than pool_count:
                Let block be proc list_get from List with alloc_pool, i
                If block is not equal to 0:
                    proc deallocate from Layout with block
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
            proc list_destroy from List with alloc_pool
        End If

        Let subst be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with solver, 0
        If subst is not equal to 0:
            proc list_destroy from List with subst
        End If

        Let match_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with solver, 16
        If match_registry is not equal to 0:
            proc list_destroy from List with match_registry
        End If

        Let definitions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with solver, 24
        If definitions is not equal to 0:
            proc list_destroy from List with definitions
        End If

        Let env_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with solver, 40
        If env_types is not equal to 0:
            proc list_destroy from List with env_types
        End If

        proc deallocate from Layout with solver
    End If

    Let scope_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    If scope_stack is not equal to 0:
        Let scope_count be proc list_length from List with scope_stack
        Let s be 0
        While s is less than scope_count:
            Let scope_table be proc list_get from List with scope_stack, s
            If scope_table is not equal to 0:
                proc hashtable_destroy from Dict with scope_table
            End If
            Set s to s plus 1
        End While
        proc list_destroy from List with scope_stack
    End If

    Let symbol_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    If symbol_table is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from Dict with symbol_table
    End If

    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    If type_env is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from Dict with type_env
    End If

    Let module_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    If module_table is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from Dict with module_table
    End If

    Let measure_system be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    If measure_system is not equal to 0:
        proc hashtable_destroy from Dict with measure_system
    End If

    Let error_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    If error_list is not equal to 0:
        proc list_destroy from List with error_list
    End If

    Let warning_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    If warning_list is not equal to 0:
        proc list_destroy from List with warning_list
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with analyzer
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Seeds the type environment with the built-in F# type names every program
may reference without declaration. Integer-family aliases (int, int32,
int64, nativeint), float-family aliases (float, float32, double,
single), and the remaining primitives map to their bare type codes; the
built-in polymorphic constructors Some/None (option) and Ok/Error
(Result) are registered as constructors and receive per-use fresh
instantiation in the constructor paths, so seeding stores only their
names with the polymorphic marker (payload 0, union 0) - the dedicated
built-in handling in validate_constructor_pattern and
infer_identifier_type supplies the real types.
@End Reasoning

Process called "setup_fsharp_builtins" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Seed built-in type names into the type environment

    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "int", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "int32", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "int64", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "nativeint", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "uint", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "uint32", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "uint64", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "int16", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "uint16", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "sbyte", TYPE_INT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "float", TYPE_FLOAT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "float32", TYPE_FLOAT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "double", TYPE_FLOAT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "single", TYPE_FLOAT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "decimal", TYPE_DECIMAL
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "string", TYPE_STRING
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "bool", TYPE_BOOL
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "char", TYPE_CHAR
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "unit", TYPE_UNIT
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "byte", TYPE_BYTE
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "obj", TYPE_ANY
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, "exn", TYPE_ANY

    proc setup_dotnet_members with analyzer

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers one F# core module's member surface from a compact
"name:signature;name:signature;..." table. Three key families land in
the type environment: "netmod:<Module>" marks the module name as known
(so an unknown member under a KNOWN module is a hard error while an
unknown module degrades to a warning), and "net:<Module>.<member>" maps
each member to a pooled copy of its SIGNATURE string - the real
FSharp.Core type encoded in the prefix notation member_signature_type
parses (one fresh instantiation per use site). Nested module surfaces
(Array.Parallel, List.Parallel) register under their full dotted name,
so dotted member paths of any depth resolve through the same table:
"net:Array.Parallel.map" is the member key the full identifier spelling
produces directly. Module name values are always pointers (>= 65536)
because both keys and values must be distinguishable from the
hashtable's 0-means-absent.

Signature notation (prefix grammar, one character per constructor):
  a b c d        type variables (shared within one signature)
  I F S B U C O D  int, float, string, bool, unit, char, obj/any, decimal
  > X Y          function X -> Y
  l X / r X / q X / o X   list / array / seq / option of X
  2 X / 3 X      two- / three-dimensional array of X
  E X            set of X
  M K V          map from K to V
  R              the built-in Result union (unifies by name)
  t N X1..XN     tuple of N elements (N a single digit)
@End Reasoning

Process called "seed_dotnet_module" takes analyzer as Integer, module_name as Integer, members_spec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Register a known .NET module and its member signatures

    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

    Let module_key be proc pool_concat with analyzer, "netmod:", module_name
    proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, module_key, module_key

    Let prefix be proc pool_concat with analyzer, "net:", module_name
    Set prefix to proc pool_concat with analyzer, prefix, "."

    Let spec_len be proc string_length from StringCore with members_spec
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than spec_len:
        Note: Collect the member name up to the ':' separator
        Let name_start be i
        Let scanning_name be 1
        While scanning_name is equal to 1:
            If i is greater than or equal to spec_len:
                Set scanning_name to 0
                Continue
            End If
            Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with members_spec, i
            If ch is equal to 58:  Note: ':'
                Set scanning_name to 0
                Continue
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Let name_len be i minus name_start
        If name_len is equal to 0:
            Set i to i plus 1
            Continue
        End If

        Let name_buf be proc pool_allocate with analyzer, name_len plus 1
        If name_buf is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Let c be 0
        While c is less than name_len:
            Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with members_spec, name_start plus c
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with name_buf, c, ch
            Set c to c plus 1
        End While
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with name_buf, name_len, 0

        Set i to i plus 1  Note: Skip ':'

        Note: Collect the signature text up to the ';' separator
        Let sig_start be i
        Let scanning_sig be 1
        While scanning_sig is equal to 1:
            If i is greater than or equal to spec_len:
                Set scanning_sig to 0
                Continue
            End If
            Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with members_spec, i
            If ch is equal to 59:  Note: ';'
                Set scanning_sig to 0
                Continue
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Let sig_len be i minus sig_start
        Let sig_buf be proc pool_allocate with analyzer, sig_len plus 1
        If sig_buf is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set c to 0
        While c is less than sig_len:
            Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with members_spec, sig_start plus c
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with sig_buf, c, ch
            Set c to c plus 1
        End While
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with sig_buf, sig_len, 0

        If i is less than spec_len:
            Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with members_spec, i
            If ch is equal to 59:  Note: ';'
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        End If

        Let member_key be proc pool_concat with analyzer, prefix, name_buf
        proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, member_key, sig_buf
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the standard exception constructors F# code raises without
declaration ("netexn:<Name>" keys). They type as one-argument
constructors (fresh -> exn-compatible obj) because .NET constructor
argument lists are tupled - ArgumentException("a", "b") applies the
constructor to ONE tuple expression - so a single curried step with a
fresh parameter covers every overload soundly.
@End Reasoning

Process called "seed_exception_constructors" takes analyzer as Integer, names_spec as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Register standard exception constructor names

    Let type_env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

    Let spec_len be proc string_length from StringCore with names_spec
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than spec_len:
        Let name_start be i
        Let scanning_name be 1
        While scanning_name is equal to 1:
            If i is greater than or equal to spec_len:
                Set scanning_name to 0
                Continue
            End If
            Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with names_spec, i
            If ch is equal to 59:  Note: ';'
                Set scanning_name to 0
                Continue
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Let name_len be i minus name_start
        If name_len is greater than 0:
            Let name_buf be proc pool_allocate with analyzer, name_len plus 1
            If name_buf is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
            Let c be 0
            While c is less than name_len:
                Set ch to proc string_char_at from StringCore with names_spec, name_start plus c
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with name_buf, c, ch
                Set c to c plus 1
            End While
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with name_buf, name_len, 0

            Let exn_key be proc pool_concat with analyzer, "netexn:", name_buf
            proc hashtable_set from Dict with type_env, exn_key, 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1  Note: Skip ';'
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The complete F# core surface this single-file frontend can legitimately
see: the FSharp.Core collection and value modules (List, Array, Seq,
Option, Result, String, Map, Set), the multidimensional Array2D and
Array3D modules, and the nested parallel-collection modules
(Array.Parallel, List.Parallel) - every public function registered with
its REAL FSharp.Core 6 curried signature (including the F# 6 insertAt/
removeAt/updateAt family) in the prefix notation documented at
seed_dotnet_module, plus the standard .NET and F# exception
constructors. This set is bounded and decidable, so membership is
enforced: an unknown member of one of THESE modules is a semantic error
exactly as the F# compiler reports FS0039, while modules outside the
table (System.*, user assemblies) stay permissive warnings. Real
signatures make application checking exact: partial application is
legal, an argument whose shape disagrees with the declared parameter is
an error, and applying more arguments than the signature's arrow chain
allows is an over-application error (when the chain ends in a type
variable - List.head over a list of functions - further application
remains legal, exactly as in F#). Long member tables are split across
multiple seed calls per module purely to keep source lines reviewable;
re-seeding the netmod: key is idempotent.
@End Reasoning

Process called "setup_dotnet_members" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Seed the F# core module signature registry and exception constructors

    proc seed_dotnet_module with analyzer, "List", "allPairs:>la>lblt2ab;append:>la>lala;average:>laa;averageBy:>>ab>lab;choose:>>aob>lalb;chunkBySize:>I>lalla;collect:>>alb>lalb;compareWith:>>a>aI>la>laI;concat:>qlala;contains:>a>laB;countBy:>>ab>lalt2bI;distinct:>lala;distinctBy:>>ab>lala;empty:la;exactlyOne:>laa;except:>qa>lala;exists:>>aB>laB;exists2:>>a>bB>la>lbB;filter:>>aB>lala;find:>>aB>laa;findBack:>>aB>laa;findIndex:>>aB>laI;findIndexBack:>>aB>laI;fold:>>a>ba>a>lba;fold2:>>a>b>ca>a>lb>lca;foldBack:>>a>bb>la>bb;foldBack2:>>a>b>cc>la>lb>cc;forall:>>aB>laB;forall2:>>a>bB>la>lbB;groupBy:>>ab>lalt2bla;head:>laa;indexed:>lalt2Ia;init:>I>>Iala;insertAt:>I>a>lala;insertManyAt:>I>qa>lala;isEmpty:>laB;item:>I>laa;iter:>>aU>laU;iter2:>>a>bU>la>lbU;iteri:>>I>aU>laU;iteri2:>>I>a>bU>la>lbU;last:>laa;length:>laI"
